UC10 – Configure Domain Profile / Knowledgebase (Admin/Engineer)
UC11 – Agent-Assisted Summary and Briefing (Future-facing, optional in MVP UI)
________________________________________
4. Detailed Use Cases
________________________________________
UC01 – Ingest Stakeholder Interaction from Document
Primary Actor: Business User
Goal: Convert meeting notes or correspondence (DOCX/PDF/TXT/CSV) into structured interactions, stakeholders, commitments, and issues.
Preconditions:
•	LOGOS is running and accessible via UI.
•	User has a document containing stakeholder-related content.
•	User is authenticated (if auth is enabled).
Postconditions (on success):
•	A new provisional Interaction exists in staging with extracted entities and relationships.
•	User can see a preview and proceed to UC04.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens the “Upload Interaction” screen.
2.	User selects and uploads a document (DOCX/PDF/TXT/CSV).
3.	System validates file type and size.
4.	System stores the file in staging and creates a temporary interaction_id.
5.	System extracts text from the document.
6.	System passes text to LOGOS Core NLP pipeline.
7.	LOGOS Core returns an extraction bundle (stakeholders, commitments, issues, sentiment, topics).
8.	System runs normalisation/entity resolution against existing graph.
9.	System stores a preview bundle linked to interaction_id.
10.	System notifies user that a preview is ready and opens the preview view (UC04).
Extensions / Alternatives:
•	3a. Unsupported file type
o	3a1. System rejects the file with a clear error and supported types list.
•	5a. Text extraction fails (e.g. corrupted file)
o	5a1. System flags error and logs details.
o	5a2. User is prompted to upload a different file or paste text (UC03).
•	7a. NLP pipeline unavailable (temporary failure)
o	7a1. System shows error and leaves interaction in “failed” state.
o	7a2. User can retry later.
Frequency of Use: Daily, multiple times per user.
________________________________________
UC02 – Ingest Stakeholder Interaction from Audio
Primary Actor: Business User
Goal: Convert recorded meetings or calls (audio files) into structured interactions.
Preconditions:
•	LOGOS is running and configured with a local ASR service or stub.
•	User has an audio recording they are permitted to use.
Postconditions:
•	A new provisional Interaction with transcript and extracted entities/relationships exists in staging.
•	User can proceed to UC04.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens “Upload Audio” screen.
2.	User uploads an audio file (e.g. WAV, MP3).
3.	System validates file type and size.
4.	System stores audio file and creates interaction_id.
5.	System sends audio to local ASR service.
6.	ASR returns transcript text.
7.	System passes transcript to NLP pipeline (same as UC01 steps 7–9).
8.	System saves preview bundle for interaction_id.
9.	System opens preview (UC04).
Extensions:
•	5a. ASR service unavailable or times out
o	5a1. System logs error and notifies user.
o	5a2. User may download transcript error log or try again later.
•	6a. Transcript is low quality
o	6a1. User can manually edit transcript in preview before confirmation (UC04).
Frequency: Less frequent than document ingestion but important for meeting-heavy teams.
________________________________________
UC03 – Ingest Stakeholder Interaction via Free-text Note
Primary Actor: Business User
Goal: Quickly capture a stakeholder interaction or idea directly into LOGOS as text.
Preconditions:
•	User has access to LOGOS UI.
Postconditions:
•	Provisional Interaction with provided text and extracted structure exists in staging.
•	User can proceed to UC04.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens “New Note / Interaction” form.
2.	User enters:
o	Interaction type (meeting, call, note).
o	Date/time (default to now).
o	Free-text description.
3.	User submits the form.
4.	System passes text to NLP pipeline.
5.	System receives extracted stakeholders, commitments, issues, sentiment.
6.	System performs entity resolution.
7.	System stores preview and opens UC04.
Extensions:
•	2a. User wants to skip extraction
o	2a1. User ticks “just store as note (no structured extraction)”.
o	2a2. System stores Interaction node with minimal structure and bypasses UC04.
Frequency: Frequent for quick notes and ad hoc interactions.
________________________________________
UC04 – Review and Confirm Extracted Data (Preview & Commit)
Primary Actor: Business User
Goal: Validate and correct extracted stakeholders, commitments, and issues before writing to the graph.
Preconditions:
•	A preview bundle exists in staging for a given interaction_id (from UC01/02/03).
Postconditions (on commit):
•	Interaction, stakeholders, commitments, issues, and relationships are upserted into Neo4j.
•	Preview entry is marked as committed or archived.
•	Alerts are evaluated (UC08).
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens preview view for the new interaction.
2.	System displays:
o	Interaction summary and transcript/notes.
o	Proposed stakeholders (Persons/Orgs) and links to existing or new entities.
o	Proposed commitments (text, due dates, owners, requesters).
o	Proposed issues and topics.
o	Sentiment score.
3.	User reviews stakeholders:
o	Corrects names.
o	Reassigns to different existing entities if necessary.
o	Marks some as “ignore”.
4.	User reviews commitments:
o	Edits text.
o	Assigns/changes owner.
o	Adjusts due dates.
o	Marks commitments to be created or ignored.
5.	User reviews issues and topics:
o	Confirms or removes.
o	Optionally categorises issues further.
6.	User clicks “Commit to Graph”.
7.	System builds upsert bundle and writes to Neo4j in a transaction.
8.	System confirms success and shows link to the final Interaction and stakeholder profiles.
Extensions:
•	3a. Low-confidence matches flagged
o	3a1. System visually flags low-confidence matches.
o	3a2. User must explicitly confirm or override them before commit.
•	6a. User cancels
o	6a1. System leaves preview in staging for later review.
•	7a. Graph upsert fails (DB down)
o	7a1. System shows error and logs details.
o	7a2. Preview remains available to retry later.
Frequency: Used after most ingestion events.
________________________________________
UC05 – Search for Stakeholder, Project, or Commitment
Primary Actor: Business User
Goal: Quickly find people, organisations, projects, or commitments.
Preconditions:
•	At least some data has been committed to the graph.
Postconditions:
•	User sees a list of results with relevant context and can navigate to detailed views.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User types a query into the search box (e.g. “Acme”, “SOC2 report”).
2.	User may optionally filter by type (Person, Org, Project, Commitment, Issue).
3.	System queries LOGOS Core Search Service (graph + text search).
4.	System returns ranked results (entities and interactions).
5.	User clicks a result:
o	For Person/Org → UC06 (Stakeholder 360).
o	For Project → UC09 (Project Map).
o	For Commitment → opens commitment detail with related interaction and stakeholder.
Extensions:
•	3a. No results
o	3a1. System displays “no results” and suggests broader search or different filters.
Frequency: Very frequent.
________________________________________
UC06 – View Stakeholder 360° Profile
Primary Actor: Business User, Executive Viewer
Goal: Understand the full context of a person or organisation across interactions, commitments, issues, and risks.
Preconditions:
•	Stakeholder exists in the graph (Person or Org).
•	User has navigated from search or a link.
Postconditions:
•	None beyond read-only retrieval; user may jump to related use cases (e.g. UC07, UC08).
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens a stakeholder profile (Person or Org).
2.	System retrieves from Neo4j:
o	Stakeholder attributes.
o	Associated organisations/people.
o	Interactions timeline.
o	Open and closed commitments.
o	Related projects and contracts.
o	Issues and risks linked to this stakeholder.
o	Sentiment trend over time.
o	Active alerts (if any).
3.	System calculates:
o	Influence score (graph-based).
o	Risk indicators (from alerts, commitments, sentiment).
4.	System displays:
o	Summary header (role, org, influence, risk level).
o	Timeline view of interactions.
o	Commitments list with status.
o	Charts/graphs for sentiment and risk trend.
5.	User can:
o	Drill into a specific interaction.
o	Filter the timeline (date range, topic, project).
o	Jump to related project map (UC09).
Extensions:
•	2a. Stakeholder has very limited history
o	2a1. System shows minimal info and suggests possible next steps (e.g. ingest interactions).
Frequency: Regularly used when planning engagement.
________________________________________
UC07 – Manage Commitments (Filter, Update Status)
Primary Actor: Business User
Goal: Track and maintain commitments arising from stakeholder interactions.
Preconditions:
•	Commitments exist in the system.
Postconditions:
•	Commitment statuses are updated; alerts may change accordingly.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens “Commitments” view.
2.	System shows a table of commitments with columns:
o	Text, owner, stakeholder, project/contract, due date, status, age, risk flags.
3.	User applies filters:
o	By owner (including self).
o	By stakeholder or organisation.
o	By project or contract.
o	By due date range (overdue, this week, future).
4.	User updates status:
o	Changes from “proposed” to “accepted”, or “in_progress” to “done”, etc.
5.	System writes status changes to Neo4j.
6.	System re-evaluates relevant alerts for these commitments (UC08).
7.	User can click into an individual commitment to view its originating interaction and stakeholder.
Extensions:
•	4a. Bulk update
o	4a1. User selects multiple commitments and sets a new status or due date.
o	4a2. System applies bulk update transactionally.
Frequency: Daily.
________________________________________
UC08 – View Alerts and Risk Signals
Primary Actor: Business User, Executive Viewer
Goal: See unresolved commitments, sentiment drops, and other risk signals.
Preconditions:
•	Alert rules are configured.
•	Alert evaluation job has run at least once.
Postconditions:
•	None; read-only, though follow-up actions may be triggered manually.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens “Alerts / Risks” view.
2.	System queries LOGOS Core for current alerts, including:
o	Unresolved commitments beyond thresholds.
o	Stakeholders/orgs with sentiment drops.
o	Optional project-level risk alerts (if configured).
3.	System displays alerts with:
o	Type, severity, affected stakeholder/project/owner, age, and suggested next action.
4.	User filters alerts by:
o	Type (commitments, sentiment, project).
o	Owner.
o	Stakeholder.
5.	User clicks an alert to:
o	Open relevant stakeholder profile (UC06).
o	Open commitments view (UC07).
o	Open project map (UC09).
Extensions:
•	2a. No active alerts
o	2a1. System indicates “No active alerts” and optionally displays resolved/closed alerts history.
Frequency: Regular review by managers and leads.
________________________________________
UC09 – View Project Map and Stakeholder Network
Primary Actor: Business User, Executive Viewer
Goal: See how stakeholders, commitments, issues, and risks relate to a specific project.
Preconditions:
•	Projects and related entities exist in the graph.
Postconditions:
•	None; read-only, though user may drill into related use cases.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User selects a project (via search or project list).
2.	System queries LOGOS Core for:
o	Project attributes.
o	Linked stakeholders and their roles.
o	Linked commitments, issues, risks.
o	Interactions related to the project.
3.	System visualises:
o	Graph view: Project at centre, connected to stakeholders, commitments, issues, risks.
o	Supporting tables with filters and sorting.
4.	User:
o	Zooms/pans the graph or selects subgraphs (e.g. only external stakeholders).
o	Filters by topic, risk level, or stakeholder role.
o	Clicks on nodes to open stakeholder 360 (UC06) or commitment detail.
Extensions:
•	2a. Project has minimal data
o	2a1. System shows basic structure and encourages ingestion of interactions.
Frequency: Regularly when planning engagement or reporting on project status.
________________________________________
UC10 – Configure Domain Profile / Knowledgebase
Primary Actor: System Administrator, Data/AI Engineer
Goal: Configure LOGOS for a specific domain (stakeholder engagement, contract management, etc.) without changing code.
Preconditions:
•	User has administrative access.
•	Knowledgebase and config files are accessible.
Postconditions:
•	Updated domain configuration and prompts are applied across relevant pipelines.
•	Future ingests and agent behaviours reflect new settings.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	Admin/Engineer opens configuration interface (or edits config files in repo, depending on implementation).
2.	User adjusts:
o	Domain profile selection (e.g. “stakeholder_engagement”).
o	Alert thresholds (e.g. days for unresolved commitments).
o	Lexicons, patterns, and ontologies (topics, stakeholder types, risk categories).
o	Model tier usage (rule-only vs local ML vs local LLM).
3.	User saves changes.
4.	System validates configs and reloads knowledgebase.
5.	New ingestions and queries use updated configuration.
Extensions:
•	4a. Config invalid (syntax or incompatible values)
o	4a1. System rejects the changes with clear error messages and does not apply them.
Frequency: Occasional (when tuning behaviour or expanding to new domain).
________________________________________
UC11 – Agent-Assisted Summary and Briefing (Future-facing)
Primary Actor: Business User, Executive Viewer
Goal: Obtain AI-generated summaries and briefings (e.g. for a stakeholder, project, or board pack) using LOGOS Core knowledge.
Preconditions:
•	Agent Service is configured and connected to a local LLM (or equivalent).
•	Relevant data is present in the graph.
Postconditions:
•	User receives summarised text and can click through to underlying data.
Main Success Scenario:
1.	User opens a stakeholder, project, or dashboard view.
2.	User clicks “Generate Summary / Briefing”.
3.	Agent Service:
o	Gathers relevant interactions, commitments, issues, risks, outcomes from the graph.
o	Builds a prompt using configured templates and user profile.
o	Calls the local LLM.
4.	LLM returns a structured summary/briefing.
5.	System displays the briefing, including:
o	Key stakeholders and their positions.
o	Open commitments and risks.
o	Recent changes and sentiment trends.
o	Suggested engagement actions.
6.	User can:
o	Copy the summary into reports.
o	Request refocus (e.g. “shorter”, “for execs”, “community impacts only”).
Extensions:
•	3a. LLM service unavailable
o	3a1. System shows a clear error and suggests manual report compilation using available data views.
Frequency: As needed, especially ahead of key meetings and governance forums.

